        <headline>Special Weather Statement issued April 4 at 5:50AM EDT by NWS Charleston WV</headline>
        <description>At 550 AM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking a strong thunderstorm over
Oppy, or 9 miles northwest of Williamson, moving east at 50 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 40 mph and pea size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor hail damage to vegetation is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Mount Gay, Chauncey, Myrtle, Matewan, Gilbert, Hode, Bruno, Mount
Gay-Shamrock, Williamson, Mitchell Heights, Sarah Ann, Meador, Chief
Logan State, Kermit, Verdunville, Holden, Delbarton, Hampden,
Switzer, and West Logan.

This includes Route 119 between mile markers 1 and 35.
</description>
        <instruction>If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with this storm and may lead to
localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.</instruction>
